  "prompt": "In Tagalog, what are the rules for using Nang and Ng?",
  "response": "In Tagalog, \"nang\" and \"ng\" are two different words that serve distinct grammatical functions. Here are the rules for using each:\n\n### Nang\n\"Nang\" is used in several contexts:\n\n1. **Adverbial use**: It is used to indicate manner, time, or frequency.\n   - Example: \"Umiiyak nang malakas\" (Crying loudly)\n   - Example: \"Nang umaga\" (In the morning)\n\n2. **Substitute for \"na\" and \"ng\" conjunction**: It is used as a conjunction meaning \"when\" or \"so that\".\n   - Example: \"Umalis siya nang dumating ako\" (He left when I arrived)\n   - Example: \"Mag-aral ka nang mabuti\" (Study well so that you succeed)\n\n3. **Before a verb to form infinitives**:\n   - Example: \"Nang makita\" (To see)\n\n### Ng\n\"Ng\" is used primarily in two contexts:\n\n1. **To indicate possession**: It serves as a possessive marker, equivalent to the English \u201cof\u201d.\n   - Example: \"Bahay ng guro\" (House of the teacher)\n\n2. **To mark the object of a verb**:\n   - Example: \"Kumain ng prutas\" (Ate fruit)\n   - Example: \"Nagbigay ng regalo\" (Gave a gift)\n\nUnderstanding these rules helps in grasping the nuances and proper usage of \"nang\" and \"ng\" in Tagalog sentences.",
